WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.900
So if you're new to Connect, Connect is an enterprise publishing platform for

00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:16.080
static and dynamic content that you're creating with R. So that can include

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:19.959
documents, presentations, dashboards, and Shiny applications, and basically

00:00:19.959 --> 00:00:23.719
anything that you're producing in R. It is an on-premises application, so you run

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:28.200
this on your own server behind a firewall if you want, and you're going to host it

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:32.080
on your own equipment there. And the goal is really around sharing data science

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:37.320
artifacts that you produced inside your organization. So if this is new to you, I

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:40.919
would recommend actually that you check out the introductory webinar that Bill

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:44.380
referenced a moment ago. So we recorded this two weeks ago, the recording is

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:49.160
available online, as are the slides. And I'd recommend that you start there

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:51.360
because we're going to be building on some of the foundation that we laid a

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:55.919
couple weeks ago. So if you are new to Connect, you might want to start there

00:00:55.919 --> 00:01:00.639
before you jump into some of these more advanced topics. But without any further

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:04.160
ado, let's go ahead and dive into some of the content that we want to cover today.

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:09.760
So my goal for today is really just to give you pointers to the different

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.080
tidbits that I think are important for you to know if you're going to be

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:17.680
managing RStudio Connect in a production environment. And so I won't go

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:21.480
into too much depth about a whole lot of these, but really I just kind of

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.360
want to give you links and pointers to the different things that you might be

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:28.239
interested in if you are responsible for managing a production environment with

00:01:28.239 --> 00:01:31.760
RStudio Connect. So pardon me if I'm kind of flying through some of these topics,

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:34.639
but feel free to ask questions and we can come back and do a little more

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:38.720
detail on some of these things later. Or just check out the links once

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:43.000
we post them online and hopefully you can kind of find the

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.080
information that you need there with the links that I provide. So today I want to

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:51.320
cover first of all user management, then secondly the management of resources on

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:54.480
the server, and then lastly we'll talk a little bit about kind of the system

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:59.040
management and system security implications for the server. So let's

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:03.559
dive into user management to get started. So we covered this a bit last time so I

00:02:03.559 --> 00:02:08.479
won't belabor this, but we have three different user roles on the system. The

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:12.160
first is an admin user who has all privileges on the server and they can

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:16.639
access and kind of manage anything that they need to, but irregular actions are

00:02:16.639 --> 00:02:20.380
audited and I'll dive into what that means here in a moment. Below that there

00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:23.380
would be a publisher who's someone that can upload or publish content onto the

00:02:23.380 --> 00:02:26.940
server, and then lastly there's a viewer who's just a consumer of content and

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:32.460
can't author content that gets executed on the server. So let's talk a little bit

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:36.699
about what the experience of a Connect administrator looks like. So first of all

00:02:36.699 --> 00:02:39.899
they have access to special admin only actions and so for instance this

00:02:39.899 --> 00:02:44.979
includes the admin tab, so if you're an admin on the user you're able to access

00:02:44.979 --> 00:02:48.860
certain pages within the dashboard that other users aren't able to manage that

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:52.100
shows you things like metrics, you're able to manage users and things like

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:56.259
that, and then lastly you're able to customize some application settings that

00:02:56.259 --> 00:02:59.740
other users aren't able to. So you can define vanity URLs for an application,

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:02.820
you can customize the run as argument for an application, and I'll show you

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:06.580
what all this means here in just a moment. But the trick is that you don't

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:10.580
get everything for free as an admin and so some of these things you're going to

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:14.020
be able to just hop on and start changing. Other things you're going to

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:18.300
actually have to go out of your way to explicitly grant yourself permission to

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:22.500
things that you otherwise wouldn't have had permission to do. So let's, I think

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:25.699
that's probably best covered by just an example, so let's look at an example of

00:03:25.699 --> 00:03:31.259
this. So first of all this is me logged in as an admin user on Connect.

00:03:31.259 --> 00:03:35.979
And so you can see here that first of all I have this admin tab and so that

00:03:35.979 --> 00:03:39.419
takes me first and foremost to this metrics page where I'm able to view

00:03:39.419 --> 00:03:43.179
information about the CPU and RAM usage across the server. I also have an audit

00:03:43.179 --> 00:03:47.100
logs page here where I can view kind of different changes that have been taking

00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:52.259
place on the server recently. And then lastly when I dive into particular

00:03:52.259 --> 00:03:56.500
content, even though this is not authored by me, this is authored by someone else

00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:59.899
and I don't have particular permissions on it, I am still able to go in and

00:03:59.899 --> 00:04:03.619
define custom settings for this content. So for instance here I can define a

00:04:03.619 --> 00:04:11.419
vanity URL. Let's take a look at kind of a more rich document here. So in this

00:04:11.419 --> 00:04:14.100
case we have a schedule. I as an administrator, even though I don't have

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:17.220
special privileges on this document, I can go in and customize the schedule for

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:22.100
this content. I can define a vanity URL, change the run as user, etc. So I

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:25.739
as an admin have free privileges to be able to do some of these things. However

00:04:25.739 --> 00:04:32.059
if you look at something like a document here that's private, so here I'm logged

00:04:32.059 --> 00:04:35.220
in as a different user. This is the publisher user and you can see that I

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:38.899
for this content here I've defined it to only be visible to myself. So this means

00:04:38.899 --> 00:04:42.059
that the admin user should not freely have access to this content. This is

00:04:42.059 --> 00:04:45.739
sensitive content that the admin shouldn't be able to see. And indeed if I

00:04:45.739 --> 00:04:49.500
go as the admin and I go to look at that content, this is the view that I get. So

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:52.260
you can see that I'm still able to manage the settings for that content

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:59.140
here but I do not have free access to be able to view that content. And so this is

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:02.339
kind of what we're talking about when we say the admin has the privileges to do

00:05:02.339 --> 00:05:04.980
whatever they need to do on the server but they don't get everything for free.

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:09.579
So I am not able to view this content although I can go in and I can add

00:05:09.579 --> 00:05:13.779
myself as a publisher or as a viewer because I'm able to manage the settings

00:05:13.779 --> 00:05:17.739
on this content and at that point I would be able to view the content. And so

00:05:17.739 --> 00:05:24.220
the trick here is that all of this though is managed when you make these

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:28.500
explicit actions to add or remove yourself to a particular bit of content,

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:31.820
all of those actions are going to be captured in the audit log that I

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:34.980
referenced earlier. So when I go look at the audit log you can see here that the

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:38.579
admin user assigned themselves as an owner as a collaborator on this app and

00:05:38.579 --> 00:05:42.820
then they remove themselves as an owner as a collaborator on this app. So now while I am

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:46.899
able to do everything and navigate whatever I need to cover to be able to

00:05:46.899 --> 00:05:52.019
manage the server, anytime I take those explicit options of kind of going out of

00:05:52.019 --> 00:05:55.380
my way to take special privileges on an application that's going to be captured

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:58.100
in the audit log and that's kind of the balance that we try to strike here with

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:05.019
an admin. Lastly if you've missed this in our latest release the 1.441 release we

00:06:05.019 --> 00:06:09.339
also do have the ability to download the source code for content. And again

00:06:09.339 --> 00:06:12.500
that's only available to users that are explicitly granted

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:16.140
collaborator privileges. So I as an admin do not get free access to source

00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:20.100
codes published on the server, however if I add myself as a collaborator then I am

00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:24.100
able to download the source code for an application. So this is kind of the

00:06:24.100 --> 00:06:26.899
balance that we tried to strike with an admin but I think it's important if

00:06:26.899 --> 00:06:30.179
you're going to be managing a Connect server in production that you kind of

00:06:30.179 --> 00:06:33.420
understand what the privileges of an admin actually encapsulate and what you

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:38.420
get for free and what you don't. So next we'll just kind of move on and a lot of

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:41.380
these things I'm just going to cover in rapid fire but the next one that I

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:45.059
wanted to cover is the default user role. So this is the setting that's managed in

00:06:45.059 --> 00:06:48.779
the authorization section under the default user role setting and this is

00:06:48.779 --> 00:06:51.380
basically the role that fresh users should take when they sign on to the

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:54.579
server. The default right now is publisher which means that when a user

00:06:54.579 --> 00:06:58.299
signs up on your server or when they you know log in using whatever authentication

00:06:58.299 --> 00:07:01.779
protocol you're using that user is going to become a publisher on the server

00:07:01.779 --> 00:07:05.100
they're going to have access to publish new source code. If you want to change

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:08.140
that if you want to limit that so that default so that new users coming into

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:11.859
the server are just viewers you can change this configuration setting here

00:07:11.859 --> 00:07:14.540
and make that a viewer and this is actually subject to change we've

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:18.299
considered actually making the default viewer and so in which case if you

00:07:18.299 --> 00:07:21.980
wanted the default to be publisher you could of course override that here.

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:25.220
Another tool that you should be aware of if you're managing Connect is the user

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:28.540
manager command-line interface and this is a root only command-line interface

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:32.540
that allows you to interact with Connect in kind of a batch way and so

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:34.700
right now there's kind of a limited subset of what you can do with this

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:37.660
command but we envision this growing over time to capture more of the

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:40.959
interactions that you might want to take within Connect. So right now one

00:07:40.959 --> 00:07:43.579
restriction is that the server actually does need to be stopped in order for you

00:07:43.579 --> 00:07:47.179
for you to use the command-line interface here and that that's a

00:07:47.179 --> 00:07:50.380
restriction that may be lifted here in the coming months but right now you can

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:54.140
access the tool at this location optr-studio-connect-bin-user-manager

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:57.579
and then you can run commands such as list to list all the users in the server

00:07:57.579 --> 00:08:02.179
you can run alter to change a user for instance promoting a viewer to a

00:08:02.179 --> 00:08:06.339
publisher or promoting a publisher to an admin user and you can also actually

00:08:06.339 --> 00:08:11.059
dump the audit logs even in the CSV format here so if you wanted to navigate

00:08:11.059 --> 00:08:14.859
and browse the audit logs on your own time or using your own tooling you could

00:08:14.859 --> 00:08:18.220
do that here using this user manager tool. So something you should be aware

00:08:18.220 --> 00:08:21.739
of and you can view all the documents in the admin guide for what different

00:08:21.739 --> 00:08:27.500
endpoints are available in this command. Next there's an idea of user locking in

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:30.899
the server that you should be familiar with. So as of the time of this

00:08:30.899 --> 00:08:36.700
recording in early 2017 we don't have a notion of user deletion and the reason

00:08:36.700 --> 00:08:40.140
for that is that there are a lot of open questions around what should you do with

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:44.500
a user who's deleted, what should you do with their content, should you migrate it

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:47.500
to another user, should you keep it alive on the server or should you get rid of

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:51.539
it. So until we settle some of those questions right now we've kind of

00:08:51.539 --> 00:08:54.700
settled on this compromise of user locking. So if you for instance have an

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:58.179
employee leave the company and you don't want them to have access to the server

00:08:58.179 --> 00:09:02.179
anymore you can lock their account which forbids any further login or interaction

00:09:02.179 --> 00:09:05.859
on the system they can't publish updates or new content to the server and they

00:09:05.859 --> 00:09:09.099
also don't count against your license so they're not going to count as a named

00:09:09.099 --> 00:09:11.780
user they're not going to take up the seat for your license when they're

00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:16.580
locked. And also you should be aware that you can rename users and so if your goal

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:19.700
is just to get rid of a user who's taking up a username that you want you

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:22.619
can certainly just change the username for that user and lock it and then

00:09:22.619 --> 00:09:27.460
create a new user account with the username that you desire. So that's a bit

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:30.619
about user management. We can transition into resource management now which is a

00:09:30.619 --> 00:09:34.500
bit more of a complex topic. So one of the most common questions that we get

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:37.539
around Connect is the idea of resource budgeting or how large should my server

00:09:37.539 --> 00:09:42.099
be and the problem or the difficulty in answering this question is that the

00:09:42.419 --> 00:09:47.940
requirements here almost depend entirely on what your users are deploying. So if

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:52.260
you just have a couple of simple documents that you know a couple of

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.539
simple dashboards that are updated once a day that people are going to access on

00:09:55.539 --> 00:09:58.859
your Connect server you could probably get away with some running this on you

00:09:58.859 --> 00:10:01.859
know something like very very small even you know a Raspberry Pi could probably

00:10:01.859 --> 00:10:05.979
handle that kind of workload. However if you're doing you know very intensive

00:10:05.979 --> 00:10:09.820
shiny applications that are doing you know genomic analysis on multiple

00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:13.580
gigabytes of data then your server requirements are going to be much much

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:16.859
larger. And so ideally if you if you have the luxury of being in a virtualized

00:10:16.859 --> 00:10:19.900
environment where you can kind of scale up or down a server that that would

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:24.059
probably be your best bet. But otherwise if not you can kind of run a proof of

00:10:24.059 --> 00:10:29.020
concepts and see what the hardware requirements are given the applications

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:32.260
and the types of work that your that your users are publishing to the server

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:36.020
and that's really the best way to kind of get a feel for what your requirements

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:42.340
should be in terms of hardware for the server. So in terms of the philosophy of

00:10:42.340 --> 00:10:46.039
Connect on-demand requests are largely what we're servicing when when requests

00:10:46.039 --> 00:10:49.020
are coming in and those are just going to be service best efforts. So you know

00:10:49.020 --> 00:10:51.739
as a request comes in for a shiny application we're going to do our best

00:10:51.739 --> 00:10:54.500
to spin up that shiny application and hope that there's enough memory

00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:59.140
available on the server. So but there are some knobs and some tuning that you can

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:03.299
do to cap the resource requirements available to particular applications or

00:11:03.419 --> 00:11:10.419
different different use cases. So first of all that around shiny there's there's

00:11:10.419 --> 00:11:14.460
a notion of shiny scaling. So you can scale shiny applications and connect to

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:18.659
multiple processes. So if you're not aware R is single-threaded and Connect

00:11:18.659 --> 00:11:21.940
can actually load balance a particular application across multiple independent

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:26.539
R processes running that at that same application. And so this is what's

00:11:26.539 --> 00:11:30.700
managed here in the performance tab on a shiny app. So as an admin you can go in

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:34.179
and you can override particular performance settings for an application

00:11:34.179 --> 00:11:38.380
and set for instance the number of max processes how many processes you know

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:41.179
under the heaviest load that you might be willing to run for this application.

00:11:41.179 --> 00:11:44.419
And then down at the bottom here you can see kind of some of the scaling

00:11:44.419 --> 00:11:47.859
parameters around how many connections should be supported per process. And then

00:11:47.859 --> 00:11:50.979
the load factor is basically how quickly do you want to ramp up from the minimum

00:11:50.979 --> 00:11:53.979
number of processes to the maximum number of processes as load increases.

00:11:53.979 --> 00:11:58.739
The minimum number of processes as the name implies is the is going to guarantee

00:11:58.739 --> 00:12:04.140
that in processes are running for this application at all times. The right

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:07.500
answer for this for almost all applications is zero. However if you have

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:10.580
an application that takes a really long time to start up and you don't want a

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:14.179
user hitting it having to wait multiple seconds or even minutes for the shiny

00:12:14.179 --> 00:12:17.659
application to come online you might want to define this as one or even two

00:12:17.659 --> 00:12:23.419
to ensure that that there's always a process available for incoming users. You

00:12:23.419 --> 00:12:26.979
can actually cap this if you find that users are kind of you know setting

00:12:26.979 --> 00:12:30.419
absurd minimum process values. You can actually cap this using the scheduler

00:12:30.419 --> 00:12:34.820
dot min process limit setting and that will allow you to say no application

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:39.219
should ever define a min process that's greater than X. And so that that gives

00:12:39.219 --> 00:12:44.219
you some control there. Next we've got a notion of shiny timeouts and so this

00:12:44.219 --> 00:12:47.659
currently is a globe these are global settings. Eventually we envision that

00:12:47.659 --> 00:12:51.500
these will be customizable by the application but these define two

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:55.020
different parameters. So first of all this defines the maximum amount of time

00:12:55.020 --> 00:12:58.500
that you would want to wait on an application to start. And the default is

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:02.020
60 seconds which means that if a shiny application takes longer than 60 seconds

00:13:02.020 --> 00:13:05.619
to start and come online we're going to assume that the process is having some

00:13:05.619 --> 00:13:08.659
problems and we're going to give up waiting on it. If you find that you're

00:13:08.659 --> 00:13:12.340
building shiny applications that indeed genuinely take longer than 60 seconds to

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:16.020
start you can increase this limit to say you know wait on that process a little

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:19.940
longer. The second value here is the minimum time that we should keep a

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:24.700
worker process alive after it goes idle. And so what this means is that after the

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:30.260
last user leaves process after they disconnect and the process is now empty

00:13:30.260 --> 00:13:34.659
and not serving any shiny sessions we're going to wait five seconds and if no new

00:13:34.659 --> 00:13:37.859
traffic comes in then we're going to reap that process. That's a pretty

00:13:37.859 --> 00:13:42.340
reasonable default for average workloads but again if you're running these very

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:45.780
large processes that take a lot of time or take a lot of resources to start up

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:48.979
you might not want to reap the process that quickly. You may want to leave it

00:13:48.979 --> 00:13:53.419
open for multiple minutes or hours or even overnight so that you don't have to

00:13:53.419 --> 00:13:58.820
shut down and spin up these processes which might be an expensive operation.

00:13:59.179 --> 00:14:03.780
Next we're stepping away from shiny and more into the notion of scheduled

00:14:03.780 --> 00:14:07.099
reports. We do have a throttle around report concurrency in the latest version

00:14:07.099 --> 00:14:10.979
of RStudio Connect. So this is managed in applications.schedule.concurrency

00:14:10.979 --> 00:14:14.739
and this allows you to determine the number of concurrent scheduled reports

00:14:14.739 --> 00:14:17.859
that you would ever want to run in parallel. And by default this is set

00:14:17.859 --> 00:14:23.820
to two and so if you have 20 users who all set up their documents to run every

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:27.460
night at midnight rather than trying to run all 20 of those reports at one

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:30.380
moment which you know might cause them some resource contention or even some

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:33.539
stability problems on the server we're only going to run two at a time and

00:14:33.539 --> 00:14:36.900
we'll just iterate through as quickly as we can to get all 20 reports executed

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:40.820
as close to midnight as possible. So if you find that you have more capacities

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:45.099
than two you can certainly up this limit to have multiple processes running

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:48.700
at the same moment or likewise if you need to tune that down you can.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:54.539
The next notion of resources that you might want to manage is around the disk.

00:14:54.539 --> 00:14:57.780
And so there are a few different things that we're going to store on disk.

00:14:57.780 --> 00:15:02.099
So most obviously we're hosting the applications that your users are sending us.

00:15:02.099 --> 00:15:06.419
And so first and foremost we're going to be storing on disk the content that your

00:15:06.419 --> 00:15:10.700
users upload to us. We call these bundles but these are basically the application

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:14.739
and any associated data or metadata that's associated with those applications

00:15:14.739 --> 00:15:18.020
that the user is going to give us. We store those in a compressed format and

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:22.020
basically we're storing the exact blob that the user has uploaded to us

00:15:22.020 --> 00:15:25.260
originally. We're going to we're going to keep that retain that so that you

00:15:25.260 --> 00:15:30.659
always have a copy of kind of what the user originally gave us. Next in order to

00:15:30.659 --> 00:15:33.260
actually run the application we obviously need to unzip those bundles

00:15:33.260 --> 00:15:37.020
and have them in a directory where we can actually start executing that code.

00:15:37.020 --> 00:15:40.380
And so you will have one copy of each application that's actually laid out in

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:45.179
an unzipped folder where we can actually go have R run that code and access the

00:15:45.179 --> 00:15:48.979
data associated with it if there is some. Next there's the notion of a pacrat cache

00:15:48.979 --> 00:15:52.380
and we talked about this in the last webinar but we use a system called pacrat

00:15:52.380 --> 00:15:57.700
to manage to kind of recreate the environment in terms of the R packages

00:15:57.700 --> 00:16:01.580
that are available on the publishing environment or the you know the IDE that

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:06.020
your that your user is using. We try to

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:09.179
recreate that environment and server using this pacrat system. And so what

00:16:09.179 --> 00:16:12.979
that means is that every time that a user publishes some code if they have a

00:16:12.979 --> 00:16:16.380
particular version of a particular package we're going to compile that and

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:19.739
store it on the server as well. And so you're going to have one copy of each

00:16:19.739 --> 00:16:23.219
version of each package and that is specific to the R version. So if you

00:16:23.219 --> 00:16:26.580
support multiple R versions which we'll discuss here in a moment then you might

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:32.419
have multiple copies unique to each R version. However that being said all of

00:16:32.419 --> 00:16:36.700
these are shared in the same library or same cache and so that means if you have

00:16:36.700 --> 00:16:40.619
multiple users who have published the same version of ggplot2 using the same

00:16:40.619 --> 00:16:44.099
version of R you're not going to be storing those copies redundantly they're

00:16:44.099 --> 00:16:48.059
all going to be pointing to the same singular copy of that package. So we're

00:16:48.059 --> 00:16:53.179
not we're not storing any any extra or wasted copies there but you will need to

00:16:53.179 --> 00:16:57.179
kind of budget for these. Next we store some metrics. These are usually a pretty

00:16:57.179 --> 00:17:02.460
small usage of the disk space but you know for instance you saw the RAM and

00:17:02.460 --> 00:17:06.020
CPU usage that gets stored on disk. And then lastly we store the information

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:09.219
around R processes that have executed in the past, the logs associated with

00:17:09.219 --> 00:17:14.380
them. I wouldn't expect that you'd ever see any disk concerns here unless you

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:17.780
have a user who's you know dumping multiple kilobytes of data to the log

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:20.660
each time somebody you know touches the slider on the Shiny application or

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:25.300
something absurd like that. But generally it's a pretty small consideration in

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:29.979
terms of disk. So this is just one snapshot of what our the beta.rstudio

00:17:29.979 --> 00:17:34.339
connect server looks like right now. And so you can see here that we have over

00:17:34.339 --> 00:17:37.180
2,000 applications or 2,000 bits of content that have been published to the

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:40.699
server. And we really do almost no policing on the server in terms of the

00:17:40.699 --> 00:17:43.739
bundles that are uploaded. And so if you look into this in a little bit more

00:17:43.739 --> 00:17:46.699
detail it turns out that there are a couple of applications in particular

00:17:46.699 --> 00:17:50.140
that have multiple gigabytes of data associated with them which really bloats

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:54.500
up the the bundles on the unzipped package size. And so I would expect that

00:17:54.500 --> 00:17:57.900
on a server that's actually you know if you're concerned about disk usage and you

00:17:57.900 --> 00:18:00.500
want to police this a little more tightly I suspect that you'd be able to

00:18:00.500 --> 00:18:04.500
drive this down even for a server that has lots of applications. But you can see

00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:08.099
here that for 2,000 bits of content we have 85 gigabytes of disk usage and you

00:18:08.099 --> 00:18:13.979
can kind of see kind of the ratios here of where that disk usage is coming from.

00:18:13.979 --> 00:18:19.300
So in terms of managing the disk usage and kind of putting a capacity around

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:22.540
what you want to store there are a couple of knobs that you can tune here.

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:25.420
So the first one is around bundle retention and this allows you to

00:18:25.420 --> 00:18:29.420
throttle the number of bundles that are going to be retained for each

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:35.500
application. And so as you saw as I as I previewed here a moment ago in RStudio

00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:38.660
Connect 1.4.4.1 we now have the notion of being able to roll back an

00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:41.859
application to a previous version or roll forward to a more recent version.

00:18:41.859 --> 00:18:46.420
And that is all predicated on the idea that that your old bundles are still

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:50.060
alive on disk and that you haven't reaped them. And so by default we

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:54.060
actually retain all bundles forever and that might not be what you actually want.

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:57.739
You may say that having you know five copies of an application is plenty and

00:18:57.739 --> 00:19:01.699
any version older than five versions ago you can go ahead and delete. And if

00:19:01.699 --> 00:19:04.180
that's the case then you can just customize the setting here to set that

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:07.459
to a different value other than zero. And at that point we'll we'll start

00:19:07.459 --> 00:19:12.660
deleting those those older bundles off of disk. Really here though you may find

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:16.380
more useful than actually configuring the setting just the idea of

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:20.900
introducing a policy which basically just says ask your users not to publish

00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:25.819
very large sets of data alongside their applications. And so this is really where

00:19:25.819 --> 00:19:29.939
large bundles come from is if you have you know a four gigabyte CSV file that

00:19:29.939 --> 00:19:34.180
you're wanting to analyze in some R Markdown document the naive thing to do

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:38.099
would be to bundle that four gigabyte CSV file alongside your R Markdown code

00:19:38.099 --> 00:19:41.699
publish that all as a single bundle which now means that every time that you

00:19:41.699 --> 00:19:44.699
update your R Markdown code you're republishing those four gigabytes of

00:19:44.699 --> 00:19:47.339
data which is going to consume a lot more disk space than you really need

00:19:47.339 --> 00:19:51.180
because your data presumably is not being versioned

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:56.020
alongside the code that's actually analyzing that data. And so as a best

00:19:56.020 --> 00:19:58.739
practice you should really probably provision your data separately on the

00:19:58.739 --> 00:20:02.619
server and then just publish only the source code that's going to analyze that

00:20:02.619 --> 00:20:06.060
data. And so if you push this data somewhere on the server and you make it

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:10.339
available in a you know kind of global directory where users can access it now

00:20:10.339 --> 00:20:14.380
you'd be able to have the source code you know only publish the source code in

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:17.339
the bundle that would access that data rather than having to redundantly

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:22.660
publish the data every time you make a change to your source. Next and I won't

00:20:22.660 --> 00:20:26.339
belabor this one because it's a usually a pretty small consume consumption of

00:20:26.339 --> 00:20:30.420
disk space but we do have throttles around how many jobs we're going to

00:20:30.420 --> 00:20:33.339
retain or how many process the process information that we're going to retain.

00:20:33.339 --> 00:20:38.939
So by default we say we're going to keep up to a hundred processes associated

00:20:38.939 --> 00:20:42.219
with each application and as soon as we have more than a hundred processes the

00:20:42.219 --> 00:20:45.619
oldest ones are going to start getting deleted and likewise any process that's

00:20:45.619 --> 00:20:48.979
older than 30 days we're going to start deleting off the disk. So as soon as

00:20:48.979 --> 00:20:51.739
either of these constraints is violated the job is going to be deleted from disk

00:20:51.739 --> 00:20:55.420
we won't have the process logs associated with that anymore. If you're

00:20:55.420 --> 00:20:58.380
in an environment that's highly audited and you need to make sure that you have

00:20:58.380 --> 00:21:02.739
you know the logs associated internally you can customize these settings to keep

00:21:02.739 --> 00:21:08.900
older copies of jobs or more copies of jobs for each application. So kind of a

00:21:08.900 --> 00:21:11.420
larger picture than a few things that you should consider from an IT

00:21:11.540 --> 00:21:16.699
perspective. So first of all you can manage the server.data.dir setting which

00:21:16.699 --> 00:21:19.500
by default is going to be var lib RStudio Connect. That's where we're going

00:21:19.500 --> 00:21:23.219
to store our variable size data associated with Connect. If you have an

00:21:23.219 --> 00:21:26.819
NFS share or something larger where you know you want kind of the bulky data

00:21:26.819 --> 00:21:30.380
stored for Connect you can customize that setting and we'll put all the

00:21:30.380 --> 00:21:34.900
data there. So in reality if you can keep the bundle sizes small the disk usage

00:21:34.900 --> 00:21:38.739
should be probably under 100 gigabytes for a kind of medium traffic server.

00:21:38.739 --> 00:21:41.780
If you're expecting that you're dealing with large data sets and people are

00:21:41.780 --> 00:21:45.699
going to be publishing large bundles you might want more than that. But obviously

00:21:45.699 --> 00:21:49.020
if you have the luxury of being an environment where you can have kind of a

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:55.619
scalable disk volume that would be the most ideal. But you're going to get the

00:21:55.619 --> 00:21:59.339
best performance out of a fast disk so something like SSD is usually

00:21:59.339 --> 00:22:03.339
appropriate for the kind of workloads that we're using here. An NFS should be

00:22:03.339 --> 00:22:06.020
fine although you should consider performance make sure that it's a

00:22:06.020 --> 00:22:11.060
performant network share. And do be aware that the SQLite database which can

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:14.859
be pulled out separately from from this data directory must be on local disk.

00:22:14.859 --> 00:22:17.660
That cannot be on NFS. So that's everything other than the SQLite

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:23.060
database can be shared in NFS. And we discussed that a bit in the last

00:22:23.060 --> 00:22:28.099
webinar so I won't go into more detail there. If you well sorry when you want to

00:22:28.099 --> 00:22:32.060
run backups for RStudio Connect you know you can certainly use a snapshotting

00:22:32.060 --> 00:22:36.579
system if you have you know that that luxury on your on your disk volumes. If

00:22:36.579 --> 00:22:39.780
you don't have snapshotting then and you actually want to run a manual backup

00:22:39.780 --> 00:22:43.060
then here are a couple directories that you should consider including in your

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:47.459
backups. So first of all obviously the var lib RStudio Connect directory which

00:22:47.459 --> 00:22:50.380
is going to have all the all the data that we referenced earlier on bundles

00:22:50.380 --> 00:22:54.619
and applications and process logs etc. And you should also consider including

00:22:54.619 --> 00:22:57.900
etc RStudio Connect. This is going to include your config file and then some

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:01.459
other peripheral files that might be used to manage the server. And then of

00:23:01.459 --> 00:23:04.780
course if you pulled your database out because of you know NFS concerns or

00:23:04.780 --> 00:23:09.060
anything like that then be sure that you backup your database as well. In order to

00:23:09.060 --> 00:23:12.619
do this you do need to bring the server offline run the backup in order to get a

00:23:12.619 --> 00:23:17.219
consistent backup and then you can restart the server there. If you were

00:23:17.219 --> 00:23:21.060
unaware we do support multiple versions of R. By default we're going to at

00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:24.619
startup we're going to scan the most common locations for R and also look at

00:23:24.619 --> 00:23:27.979
the path to try to find the versions of R that you have provisioned on the

00:23:27.979 --> 00:23:31.660
server. If they're not in the most common locations or if you have R and

00:23:31.660 --> 00:23:36.260
kind of a custom directory you can register those explicit R locations

00:23:36.260 --> 00:23:39.459
wherever they are in your server. And all of this is documented in the Admin

00:23:39.459 --> 00:23:43.739
Guide at the link that I referenced below. And now what's going to happen

00:23:43.739 --> 00:23:48.540
then is every time that a user publishes you're going to we're going to do our

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:52.140
best to align the version of R that they're using to the version of R that

00:23:52.140 --> 00:23:55.380
to the versions of R that you have available on the server. And there are a

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:58.699
few different alignment algorithms that we have available all of which are again

00:23:58.699 --> 00:24:02.900
are described in this link here that I mentioned there. And so that would define

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:06.859
kind of how we go from the client version of R that they're using to find

00:24:06.859 --> 00:24:09.900
the appropriate server version of R that you would want to use to associate with

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:15.500
that. Another feature that you should be aware of is the notion of a process

00:24:15.500 --> 00:24:19.219
supervisor. And so this is basically a prefix that will provide entity R

00:24:19.219 --> 00:24:22.939
process invocation. This is defined in applications.supervisor. And for

00:24:22.939 --> 00:24:26.540
instance we provide the example here of running nice which is a Linux command if

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:30.219
you're unfamiliar that allows you to kind of set the process priority for a

00:24:30.219 --> 00:24:33.780
given application. And so this is a prefix that we're going to run before

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:38.619
spawning R. And so in this case we're going to say give the nice priority level

00:24:38.619 --> 00:24:45.140
2 and then invoke R. If for instance you have a shell script that needs to be run

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:48.939
before running R in order to provision certain resources on the server you

00:24:48.939 --> 00:24:51.979
could use this to kind of define a custom shell script that's going to run

00:24:51.979 --> 00:24:55.579
before running R. And there are some caveats around how you should invoke

00:24:55.579 --> 00:24:59.099
this and how it kind of needs to behave but all of this is documented at the link

00:24:59.099 --> 00:25:03.619
that I provide here. So if you're in a world where you do need to provision

00:25:03.619 --> 00:25:08.900
certain resources before spawning R this may be of interest to you. Secondly

00:25:08.900 --> 00:25:16.140
there's the notion of customizer run as user. So RStudio Connect has a

00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:20.979
certain user that we're going to invoke R as. So the Connect server itself is

00:25:20.979 --> 00:25:25.060
going to run as root but we don't spawn R as root. So we're going to spawn R as

00:25:25.060 --> 00:25:28.219
the user RStudio Connect by default which is a user that gets created when

00:25:28.219 --> 00:25:31.260
you run the installer. And the primary group for that user is the RStudio

00:25:31.260 --> 00:25:34.339
Connect group. And all of this is described in more detail at this link.

00:25:34.339 --> 00:25:38.420
But you can actually go in and start customizing that. And so if you define

00:25:38.420 --> 00:25:42.060
globally a new application start run as user you can say I don't want to run R

00:25:42.060 --> 00:25:44.939
as the RStudio Connect user by default I want to run it as someone else. And

00:25:44.939 --> 00:25:48.540
that's totally fine and you can change that globally. You can also change that

00:25:48.540 --> 00:25:51.780
per application. And so this is configured in the dashboard and you do

00:25:51.780 --> 00:25:57.219
have to have admin privileges in order to change the setting. So only an admin

00:25:57.219 --> 00:26:01.699
can modify the setting but basically this allows you to go in inside the

00:26:01.699 --> 00:26:05.099
dashboard to a particular application and say rather than running as the

00:26:05.099 --> 00:26:09.300
default user which again by default is RStudio Connect rather than running as

00:26:09.300 --> 00:26:14.020
that user I want to run as a different user on the server. And so for this

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:16.979
particular process you can have it execute as a different user on the

00:26:16.979 --> 00:26:20.099
server. And that allows you to make special system resources that may be

00:26:20.099 --> 00:26:24.780
available only to particular users available to certain applications. And so

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:27.939
perhaps globally you want all your processes to run as RStudio Connect

00:26:27.939 --> 00:26:32.260
user but there may be certain applications that require special access

00:26:32.260 --> 00:26:37.180
to disk resources. If you're following that pattern of provisioning data on the

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:40.739
server before you know separate from the bundle perhaps you want to actually

00:26:40.739 --> 00:26:44.579
customize and segment off certain data sets and say only certain applications

00:26:44.579 --> 00:26:47.420
should have access to them. So you can do this using the standard Linux file

00:26:47.420 --> 00:26:50.859
permissions and then you can just have the R applications that should have

00:26:50.859 --> 00:26:54.420
access to those data sets run as a certain user who would have access to

00:26:54.420 --> 00:26:58.579
them on the server. So that's certainly a feature that you should consider and be

00:26:58.579 --> 00:27:03.380
aware of if you're in the world of trying to customize access to particular

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:08.300
system resources based on individual R applications. And do be aware that

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:12.900
any user that you specify does have to be a member of the primary group of

00:27:12.900 --> 00:27:16.619
the default run as user which again is the RStudio Connect group. So you can't

00:27:16.619 --> 00:27:20.500
just go in and specify any Unix user on the system and have them start invoking

00:27:20.500 --> 00:27:23.780
R. You would actually need to make sure that those users are members of the

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:27.540
RStudio Connect group before they would be eligible or they would be candidates

00:27:27.540 --> 00:27:32.859
to execute R through RStudio Connect. You can actually take this one step further

00:27:32.859 --> 00:27:36.699
by enabling another setting which is applications.runAsCurrentUser and

00:27:36.699 --> 00:27:40.660
now this does require PAM authentication and it defaults to false which is

00:27:40.660 --> 00:27:44.859
disabled. But if you go in and you disable the setting and you're using PAM

00:27:44.859 --> 00:27:48.099
then what that actually means is that you could have a Shiny application that

00:27:48.099 --> 00:27:52.819
rather than running as a hard-coded user or even a custom hard-coded user this

00:27:52.819 --> 00:27:56.380
the Shiny application will actually run as the user who is viewing the

00:27:56.380 --> 00:28:00.780
application. And so again if you know this does require PAM because that means

00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:04.859
that the user you know the user has already logged into the system we know

00:28:04.859 --> 00:28:08.099
that their username is a valid Linux account on the server and so we can

00:28:08.099 --> 00:28:12.180
actually go out now and start running the R process as them which means that

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:15.540
your Shiny application you know for instance if you're if you're in like a

00:28:15.540 --> 00:28:18.780
Kerberos environment or something like that where you have particular resources

00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:22.260
that are available to every user on the system and you want to know that the R

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:25.699
processes are the Shiny interactions that they're having are actually based

00:28:25.699 --> 00:28:30.020
on the R processes running specifically as that user then this is a way to

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:32.780
accomplish that and all of this again is documented in the admin guide at this

00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:39.380
link here that I provide. We also do support PAM sessions and so if you want

00:28:39.380 --> 00:28:43.099
to use PAM to kind of provision additional resources before spawning R

00:28:43.099 --> 00:28:47.180
you can specify a custom PAM service and more documentation is available in the

00:28:47.180 --> 00:28:51.900
admin guide there. Alright so then moving on to the last section here around

00:28:51.900 --> 00:28:54.540
system security and kind of some of the considerations that you should be

00:28:54.540 --> 00:28:59.300
available that you should be aware of from a security standpoint. So first of

00:28:59.300 --> 00:29:03.579
all as I suspect most of us know HTTPS is very important and so if you're

00:29:03.579 --> 00:29:07.339
accepting usernames and passwords through your system then then you should

00:29:07.339 --> 00:29:12.140
almost certainly be using TLS encryption or error HTTPS and so this is pretty

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:16.900
simple to define you just set up the HTTPS section you set up the listen and

00:29:16.900 --> 00:29:20.619
the key and the certificate settings to define what port and what certificate

00:29:20.619 --> 00:29:24.500
and what key you want to use for HTTPS. You can also set up the HTTP redirect

00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:28.859
which will say for instance if you want to listen on port 80 for HTTP requests

00:29:28.939 --> 00:29:33.459
and forward them on to HTTPS then this is a way that allows you to do that all

00:29:33.459 --> 00:29:37.219
self-contained within the server and this is something that you should really

00:29:37.219 --> 00:29:43.459
pretty strongly consider especially if you're accepting usernames and passwords.

00:29:43.459 --> 00:29:47.180
Another thing that you can consider here around security implications would be

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:50.859
the notion of browser security and so there are a few different options that

00:29:50.859 --> 00:29:54.140
you can configure all of which are documented in more detail at the link

00:29:54.140 --> 00:29:57.900
that I provide here but we do support HSTS we have content type sniffing

00:29:57.900 --> 00:30:01.300
customization you can change the X frame options and you can even define

00:30:01.300 --> 00:30:04.099
custom HTTP headers that you want included on all requests that are going

00:30:04.099 --> 00:30:07.660
out of the server and the best way to kind of verify that you've got some of

00:30:07.660 --> 00:30:12.060
these settings available is SSL labs provides a great tool and if you go to

00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:14.619
this link here you can actually point this at your server assuming that it's

00:30:14.619 --> 00:30:18.180
public you can point this at your server and it'll run a suite of tests against

00:30:18.180 --> 00:30:23.060
first of all your SSL certificate but also it'll kind of confirm that that you

00:30:23.060 --> 00:30:26.020
have all these settings set appropriately and that your server is

00:30:26.020 --> 00:30:30.859
appropriately locked down. I alluded to this earlier but we do support audit

